---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';

const timeline = [
  { year: '1955', text: 'Harrison Shull joins the IU chemistry faculty, having worked with Per-Olov Löwdin at Uppsala on natural orbital theory.' },
  { year: '1959', text: 'IU establishes its Research Computing Center, with Shull as its first director.' },
  { year: '1961', text: 'Ernest R. Davidson earns his PhD in theoretical chemistry at IU Bloomington.' },
  { year: '1963', text: 'The Quantum Chemistry Program Exchange begins operation at Bloomington — the first organized way for chemists anywhere to share code.' },
  { year: '1970s', text: 'Attila Szabo, on the IU faculty, writes Modern Quantum Chemistry with Neil Ostlund.' },
  { year: '1981', text: 'The QCPE Newsletter becomes the QCPE Bulletin, giving programs citable numbers.' },
  { year: '1984', text: 'Davidson returns to IU as a member of the faculty.' },
  { year: '2001', text: 'Davidson receives the National Medal of Science while at IU.' },
  { year: '2003', text: 'The Harrison Shull Lectureship in Chemistry is established.' },
  { year: '2007', text: 'QCPE closes after 44 years, its function long since absorbed by the internet it predated.' },
];

const sources = [
  { label: 'Quantum Chemistry Program Exchange — Wikipedia', href: 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Quantum_Chemistry_Program_Exchange' },
  { label: 'Harrison Shull — Wikipedia', href: 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Harrison_Shull' },
  { label: 'The Harrison Shull Lectureship in Chemistry — IU Department of Chemistry', href: 'https://www.chem.indiana.edu/news-events/distinguished-lecture-series/the-harrison-shull-lectureship-in-chemistry/' },
  { label: 'Ernest R. Davidson — National Medal of Science, U.S. National Science Foundation', href: 'https://www.nsf.gov/honorary-awards/national-medal-science/recipients/ernest-r-davidson' },
  { label: 'IU chemist Davidson to receive National Medal of Science — IU News Room', href: 'https://newsinfo.iu.edu/news/page/normal/389.html' },
  { label: 'Ernest Davidson — IU Department of Chemistry', href: 'https://www.chem.indiana.edu/faculty/ernest-davidson/' },
  { label: 'Peter J. Ortoleva — IU University Honors and Awards', href: 'https://honorsandawards.iu.edu/awards/honoree/1123.html' },
  { label: 'Attila Szabo (scientist) — Wikipedia', href: 'https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Attila_Szabo_(scientist)' },
  { label: 'Quantum Chemistry Program Exchange, Facilitator of Theoretical and Computational Chemistry in Pre-Internet History (ACS Symposium Series, 2013)', href: 'https://pubs.acs.org/doi/abs/10.1021/bk-2013-1122.ch008' },
];
---

<BaseLayout
  title="History — IU Theoretical Chemistry"
  description="Indiana University's role in the history of computational chemistry, from the Quantum Chemistry Program Exchange to the faculty who built the field."
>
  <p class="eyebrow">History</p>
  <h1>A Long History in Computing Chemistry</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Theoretical chemistry at Indiana University is older than most of the software the
    field now runs on. For 44 years, if you wanted a quantum chemistry program, you wrote
    to Bloomington.
  </p>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-head">
      <h2>The Quantum Chemistry Program Exchange</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        Before the internet, scientific software moved by mail. In 1963, Harrison Shull
        founded the <strong>Quantum Chemistry Program Exchange</strong> (QCPE) at IU
        Bloomington as an inexpensive way for chemists to exchange programs rather than
        each rewrite the same integrals code. It was, in effect, the field's package
        repository — three decades before that phrase existed.
      </p>
      <p>
        The catalog reached nearly 100 programs within three years and passed 400 by the
        mid-1980s, when membership exceeded 2,000. Distribution followed the media of each
        era in turn: punched cards, then magnetic tape, floppy disks, CD-ROMs, and finally
        FTP. From 1981 the <em>QCPE Bulletin</em> gave each program a citable number, and
        citations to those numbers peaked above 1,000 per year in the early 1990s.
      </p>
      <p>
        Much of the field passed through the catalog. Gaussian was distributed as QCPE
        entries #236, #368, and #406 before becoming commercial; MOPAC later became the
        most requested program. POLYATOM, CNDO/2, AMPAC, CRYSTAL, Molden, and the MM2 and
        MM3 force fields all moved through Bloomington. Originally funded by the Air Force
        Office of Scientific Research and later the NSF, QCPE became self-sustaining in
        1973 and operated until 2007.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-head">
      <h2>The people who built it</h2>
    </div>

    <article class="thrust">
      <h3>Harrison Shull</h3>
      <p class="who">IU faculty 1955–1979 · Professor and chair of chemistry</p>
      <p>
        Shull came to IU in 1955, having worked with Per-Olov Löwdin at Uppsala on natural
        orbital theory — a foundational contribution to how electron correlation is treated
        in electronic structure calculations. He recognized early what digital computing
        would mean for chemistry, becoming the first director of IU's Research Computing
        Center in 1959 and founding QCPE in 1963. He was elected to the National Academy of
        Sciences in 1969 and wrote over 140 papers. He later served as provost of Rensselaer,
        chancellor of CU Boulder, and provost of the Naval Postgraduate School. The Harrison
        Shull Lectureship, established in 2003, still brings an outstanding computational
        chemist to Bloomington each year.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="thrust">
      <h3>Richard W. Counts</h3>
      <p class="who">Manager, Quantum Chemistry Program Exchange</p>
      <p>
        Shull founded QCPE; Richard Counts ran it. He managed the exchange for most of its
        existence — the decades in which the catalog grew from a handful of programs past
        400, membership climbed beyond 2,000, and the <em>QCPE Bulletin</em> turned shared
        code into something citable. It was infrastructure work rather than headline
        science, and the field depended on it completely: for a generation of chemists,
        obtaining a program meant writing to Bloomington, and the person on the other end
        of that correspondence was Counts.
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="thrust">
      <h3>Ernest R. Davidson</h3>
      <p class="who">PhD, IU 1961 · IU faculty 1984–2002 · Distinguished Professor Emeritus</p>
      <p>
        Davidson earned his PhD in theoretical chemistry at IU in 1961 and returned to the
        faculty in 1984, holding the Robert and Marjorie Mann Chair. Two methods carry his
        name and remain in daily use: the <strong>Davidson correction</strong>, which
        estimates the effect of higher excitations on a truncated CI energy, and
        <strong>Davidson diagonalization</strong>, the iterative algorithm that makes large
        CI eigenvalue problems tractable at all. Essentially every modern electronic
        structure package contains a descendant of the latter.
      </p>
      <p>
        He authored more than 400 publications and <em>Reduced Density Matrices in Quantum
        Chemistry</em> (1976), and was elected to the National Academy of Sciences in 1987.
        In 2001, while on the IU faculty, he received the
        <strong>National Medal of Science</strong> — cited for the developments "that led to
        the field of computational quantum chemistry and made possible the accurate modeling
        of chemical reactions and the response of molecules to radiation."
      </p>
    </article>

    <article class="thrust">
      <h3>Peter J. Ortoleva</h3>
      <p class="who">Distinguished Professor Emeritus of Chemistry · Adjunct Professor of Physics</p>
      <p>
        Ortoleva's work on reaction, transport, and mechanical systems crossed freely
        between chemistry, physics, geology, and informatics. His research on geochemical
        self-organization reshaped thinking in geological circles by showing that many
        repetitive patterns in the Earth's crust could arise spontaneously, without an
        externally imposed template — with applications from petroleum exploration to
        earthquake hazard reduction. A second effort built physical-chemical models and
        simulators of the living cell, aimed at drug targeting and bioremediation.
      </p>
    </article>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-head">
      <h2>The book on every theorist's shelf</h2>
    </div>
    <div class="prose">
      <p>
        <strong>Attila Szabo</strong> was a member of the IU chemistry faculty in the 1970s.
        While at Indiana he wrote, with fellow Karplus-group alumnus <strong>Neil S.
        Ostlund</strong>, the book that generations of students have simply called
        "Szabo and Ostlund": <em>Modern Quantum Chemistry: Introduction to Advanced
        Electronic Structure Theory</em>.
      </p>
      <p>
        Published by Macmillan in 1982, revised by McGraw-Hill in 1989, and kept in print
        by Dover since 1996, it remains the standard introduction to electronic structure
        theory more than forty years on — still the first book handed to most incoming
        theory graduate students. Szabo went on to the National Institutes of Health, where
        he leads the Theoretical Biophysical Chemistry Section.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-head">
      <h2>Timeline</h2>
    </div>
    <ol class="timeline">
      {
        timeline.map((item) => (
          <li>
            <span class="year">{item.year}</span>
            <span class="event">{item.text}</span>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ol>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="section-head">
      <h2>Sources</h2>
    </div>
    <ul class="sources">
      {
        sources.map((s) => (
          <li>
            <a href={s.href}>{s.label}</a>
          </li>
        ))
      }
    </ul>
  </section>
</BaseLayout>

<style>
  .timeline {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0;
    border-left: 2px solid var(--rule);
  }

  .timeline li {
    display: grid;
    grid-template-columns: 5.5rem 1fr;
    gap: 0 1.25rem;
    padding: 0.7rem 0 0.7rem 1.5rem;
    position: relative;
  }

  .timeline li::before {
    content: '';
    position: absolute;
    left: -5px;
    top: 1.25rem;
    width: 8px;
    height: 8px;
    border-radius: 50%;
    background: var(--crimson);
  }

  .timeline .year {
    font-family: ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;
    font-size: 0.875rem;
    font-weight: 600;
    color: var(--crimson);
    letter-spacing: 0.02em;
  }

  .timeline .event {
    max-width: var(--measure);
  }

  @media (max-width: 34rem) {
    .timeline li {
      grid-template-columns: 1fr;
      gap: 0.15rem;
    }
  }

  .sources {
    list-style: none;
    padding: 0;
    margin: 0;
    font-family: ui-sans-serif, system-ui, sans-serif;
    font-size: 0.875rem;
  }

  .sources li {
    border-bottom: 1px solid var(--rule);
    max-width: var(--measure);
  }

  .sources a {
    display: flex;
    align-items: center;
    min-height: 44px;
    padding-block: 0.5rem;
  }
</style>
